{"TopicId":186560,"ForumId":44,"TopicTitle":"[New] Space Launch System / Orion Discussion Thread","CreatedByName":"ZooNamedGames","CreatedById":103726,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-07-21T02:48:55Z","PageNum":125,"Articles":[{"CreatedByName":"tater","CreatedById":119411,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-22T03:27:07Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022FiIw0vCXkAA_hyh?format=jpg\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 data-ratio=\u002275.00\u0022 height=\u0022768\u0022 width=\u00221024\u0022 src=\u0022https://pbs.twimg.com/media/FiIw0vCXkAA_hyh?format=jpg\u0022\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"cubinator","CreatedById":150330,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-22T04:10:28Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAmazing to be able to see the far side like that, and just in general to watch live.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"darthgently","CreatedById":204885,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-22T04:46:15Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nNot certain, but it does appear CAPSTONE will operate as a relay.\u00A0 I can\u0027t see any other reasonable interpretation of this paragraph.\u00A0 There is surely a better source than Gizmodo with better reporting but this came up quick in a search. (from last paragraph)\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cem\u003E\u0022\u003Cspan style=\u0022background-color:#ffffff;color:#222222;font-size:17px;\u0022\u003EThe next step for CAPSTONE, aside from the final clean-up maneuvers, is to test the CAPS software developed by Advanced Space. CAPS should make it possible for spacecraft to communicate with other spacecraft, reducing the need for ground stations to mediate these sessions. This will become increasingly important as more satellites are sent to the Moon in the coming years, and as NASA and its international partners work to build a sustainable crewed\u003Cspan\u003E\u00A0\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022background-color:#ffffff;color:#222222;font-size:17px;\u0022\u003Epresence in the lunar environment.\u0022\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/em\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022background-color:#ffffff;color:#222222;font-size:17px;\u0022\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022https://gizmodo.com/capstone-reaches-orbit-around-moon-1849779300\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://gizmodo.com/capstone-reaches-orbit-around-moon-1849779300\u003C/a\u003E\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/em\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"tater","CreatedById":119411,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-22T14:03:22Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://video.ibm.com/channel/b4dEcL3bJKW\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://video.ibm.com/channel/b4dEcL3bJKW\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nLive view from Artemis I.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsEmbeddedOther\u0022\u003E\n\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 data-controller=\u0022core.front.core.autosizeiframe\u0022 data-embedid=\u0022embed4303698775\u0022 scrolling=\u0022no\u0022 src=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?app=core\u0026amp;module=system\u0026amp;controller=embed\u0026amp;url=https://twitter.com/space_pete/status/1594898217434550275\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Gargamel","CreatedById":64714,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-22T15:27:33Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThe new Earthrise pic is nice. \u00A0\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"SunlitZelkova","CreatedById":206402,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-22T21:18:00Z","Content":"\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsEmbeddedOther\u0022\u003E\n\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 data-controller=\u0022core.front.core.autosizeiframe\u0022 data-embedid=\u0022embed4976884316\u0022 scrolling=\u0022no\u0022 src=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?app=core\u0026amp;module=system\u0026amp;controller=embed\u0026amp;url=https://twitter.com/nasa_marshall/status/1595096021079564288?s=46%26t=4bl9AZjH8vN1rSa5kj1IVw\u0022 style=\u0022height:561px;\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nDeceased Apollo LM engineers must be rolling in their graves.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThey could at least say capsule. Instead they have gone from \u201Cspacecraft\u201D to \u201Cspacecraft designed for humans\u201D, which ironically makes it explicitly include the LM ascent stage. At least \u201Cspacecraft\u201D could be passed off as a categorization mistake!\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThis is the equivalent of me being an aviation engineer, building the world\u2019s highest flying crewed aircraft, and saying the people in it \u201Cwill fly higher than any human ever before\u201D.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI\u2019ll add it either means NASA PR people and the engineers who go along with this don\u2019t know much about Apollo, or they are deliberately ignoring facts for PR purposes.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nMakes sense given SLS\u2019 justification (and to a certain extent Orion\u2019s too) is based on ignoring the existence of Commercial Crew vehicles and Starship.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Barzon","CreatedById":185383,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-22T23:19:08Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI really hope they share a video of Orion\u0027s party mode at some point.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222022-11-22T23:22:59Z\u0022 title=\u002211/22/2022 11:22  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00221 yr\u0022\u003ENovember 22, 2022\u003C/time\u003E by Barzon\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Beccab","CreatedById":208000,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-23T06:46:44Z","Content":"\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsEmbeddedOther\u0022\u003E\n\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 data-controller=\u0022core.front.core.autosizeiframe\u0022 data-embedid=\u0022embed7118191145\u0022 scrolling=\u0022no\u0022 src=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?app=core\u0026amp;module=system\u0026amp;controller=embed\u0026amp;url=https://mobile.twitter.com/NASAMoon/status/1595168563802869773\u0022 style=\u0022height:544px;\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nNooooooooo\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Codraroll","CreatedById":163815,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-23T09:27:23Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224201497\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022186560\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221669151880\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022206402\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022SunlitZelkova\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n12 hours ago, SunlitZelkova said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nDeceased Apollo LM engineers must be rolling in their graves.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThey could at least say capsule. Instead they have gone from \u201Cspacecraft\u201D to \u201Cspacecraft designed for humans\u201D, which ironically makes it explicitly include the LM ascent stage. At least \u201Cspacecraft\u201D could be passed off as a categorization mistake!\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThis is the equivalent of me being an aviation engineer, building the world\u2019s highest flying crewed aircraft, and saying the people in it \u201Cwill fly higher than any human ever before\u201D.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThe terminology here has all sorts of fun technicalities. The farthest distance traveled by any craft designed for humans might be a certain Tesla Roadster, although it wasn\u0027t designed for humans in the regime of space.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nBut in either case, I guess\u00A0\u003Cem\u003ESnoopy\u003C/em\u003E, the Lunar Landing Module tested during Apollo 10 and subsequently ejected into a heliocentric orbit, comfortably beats Orion on every relevant metric.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Minmus Taster","CreatedById":206159,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-23T12:39:57Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224201602\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022186560\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221669186004\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022208000\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Beccab\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n5 hours ago, Beccab said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsEmbeddedOther\u0022\u003E\n\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 data-controller=\u0022core.front.core.autosizeiframe\u0022 data-embedid=\u0022embed3791596243\u0022 scrolling=\u0022no\u0022 src=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?app=core\u0026amp;module=system\u0026amp;controller=embed\u0026amp;url=https://mobile.twitter.com/NASAMoon/status/1595168563802869773\u0022 style=\u0022height:712px;\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nNooooooooo\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler\u0022 data-ipsspoiler=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler_header\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cspan\u003ESpoiler\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsEmbeddedVideo\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv\u003E\n\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 frameborder=\u00220\u0022 height=\u0022150\u0022 src=\u0022https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/rY0WxgSXdEE?feature=oembed\u0022 title=\u0022Queen - Another One Bites the Dust (Official Video)\u0022 width=\u0022200\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"cubinator","CreatedById":150330,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-23T14:08:21Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224201626\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022186560\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221669195643\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022163815\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Codraroll\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n4 hours ago, Codraroll said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThe terminology here has all sorts of fun technicalities. The farthest distance traveled by any craft designed for humans might be a certain Tesla Roadster, although it wasn\u0027t designed for humans in the regime of space.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nBut in either case, I guess\u00A0\u003Cem\u003ESnoopy\u003C/em\u003E, the Lunar Landing Module tested during Apollo 10 and subsequently ejected into a heliocentric orbit, comfortably beats Orion on every relevant metric.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nHowever, Snoopy was not intended to carry humans to the distance it achieved, whereas Orion was.\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"sevenperforce","CreatedById":157695,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-23T14:50:22Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224201693\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022186560\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221669212501\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022150330\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022cubinator\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n58 minutes ago, cubinator said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224201626\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022186560\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221669195643\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022163815\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Codraroll\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n5 hours ago, Codraroll said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThe terminology here has all sorts of fun technicalities. The farthest distance traveled by any craft designed for humans might be a certain Tesla Roadster, although it wasn\u0027t designed for humans in the regime of space.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nBut in either case, I guess\u00A0\u003Cem\u003ESnoopy\u003C/em\u003E, the Lunar Landing Module tested during Apollo 10 and subsequently ejected into a heliocentric orbit, comfortably beats Orion on every relevant metric.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nHowever, Snoopy was not intended to carry humans to the distance it achieved, whereas Orion was.\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u0022Orion will be entering a distant retrograde orbit beyond the moon, breaking the record set by Apollo 13 for the [greatest distance from Earth achieved] by a [pressurized spacecraft with sufficient internal volume to hold multiple humans and an outer mold line suitable for controlled atmospheric re-entry] at 248,655 miles from Earth.\u0022\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAlthough I wonder if even that is true. It seems to me that there\u0027s a pretty substantial difference between the distance to the Moon at perigee and at apogee, which might need to be taken into consideration.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAt perigee, the moon can be as close to Earth as 356,400 km (221,500 miles), while at apogee it can be as far as 406,700 km (252,700 miles).\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSo if any of the Apollo missions took place close to apogee, their command module parking orbits may well have been farther from Earth\u0027s surface than Orion.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIt\u0027s also unclear whether the number provided by NASA above is actually a measurement of distance from Earth\u0027s surface or if it is based on distance from the center of the Earth.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222022-11-23T15:08:02Z\u0022 title=\u002211/23/2022 03:08  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00221 yr\u0022\u003ENovember 23, 2022\u003C/time\u003E by sevenperforce\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003Cbr\u003Eno one knows\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Gargamel","CreatedById":64714,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-23T15:41:04Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSince it\u2019s unmanned, I don\u2019t think it should qualify for any record, it\u2019s just an elaborate probe with extra shiny. \u00A0 \u00A0Snoopy, however, was manned at some point in its mission, and should count for something. \u00A0 \u00A0Once Artemis starts carrying meaty payloads, then I\u2019ll start paying attention to records. \u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Beccab","CreatedById":208000,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-23T16:14:08Z","Content":"\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsEmbeddedOther\u0022\u003E\n\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 data-controller=\u0022core.front.core.autosizeiframe\u0022 data-embedid=\u0022embed795768869\u0022 scrolling=\u0022no\u0022 src=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?app=core\u0026amp;module=system\u0026amp;controller=embed\u0026amp;url=https://mobile.twitter.com/jeff_foust/status/1595438460310999040\u0022 style=\u0022height:331px;\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"tater","CreatedById":119411,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-23T16:26:46Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224201745\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022186560\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221669220048\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022208000\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Beccab\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n10 minutes ago, Beccab said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsEmbeddedOther\u0022\u003E\n\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 data-controller=\u0022core.front.core.autosizeiframe\u0022 data-embedid=\u0022embed2813648234\u0022 scrolling=\u0022no\u0022 src=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?app=core\u0026amp;module=system\u0026amp;controller=embed\u0026amp;url=https://mobile.twitter.com/jeff_foust/status/1595438460310999040\u0022 style=\u0022height:331px;\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nUnconcerning I am told. Vehicle is fine.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"sevenperforce","CreatedById":157695,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-23T16:47:48Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224201712\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022186560\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221669215022\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022157695\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022sevenperforce\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n1 hour ago, sevenperforce said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIt seems to me that there\u0027s a pretty substantial difference between the distance to the Moon at perigee and at apogee, which might need to be taken into consideration.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAt perigee, the moon can be as close to Earth as 356,400 km (221,500 miles), while at apogee it can be as far as 406,700 km (252,700 miles).\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSo if any of the Apollo missions took place close to apogee, their command module parking orbits may well have been farther from Earth\u0027s surface than Orion.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIt\u0027s also unclear whether the number provided by NASA above is actually a measurement of distance from Earth\u0027s surface or if it is based on distance from the center of the Earth.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAnd of course there\u0027s \u003Ca href=\u0022http://www.astropixels.com/ephemeris/moon/moonperap2001.html\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ea website that lists all of this\u003C/a\u003E.\u00A0The moon was at apogee two days before Orion launched, on November 14, with a distance (center to center) of 404,924 km. It will be at perigee this Saturday, November 26, with a distance of 362,826 km, and it will be back at apogee on December 12, with a distance of 405,869 km.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nOrion will be Distant Retrograde Orbit from November 25-30, so its \u0022greatest distance\u0022 will be achieved with the moon closest to Earth, as shown by this mission track in the reference frame rotating with the moon (source is NASA):\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022Animation_of_Artemis_I_around_Earth_-_Fr\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 data-ratio=\u002275.00\u0022 height=\u0022420\u0022 width=\u0022560\u0022 src=\u0022https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a0/Animation_of_Artemis_I_around_Earth_-_Frame_rotating_with_Moon.gif\u0022\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022comoving.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 data-ratio=\u002264.29\u0022 height=\u0022360\u0022 width=\u0022560\u0022 src=\u0022https://i.postimg.cc/TPRMBykk/comoving.png\u0022\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nHere blue is the Earth and the green dot and line show the moon\u0027s location relative to Earth, moving between apogee and perigee. Orion only completes one half-orbit in DRO before performing the burn to take it back down to the moon, and \u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.nasa.gov/feature/around-the-moon-with-nasa-s-first-launch-of-sls-with-orion\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003ENASA states here\u003C/a\u003E that the DRO is about 70,000 km away from the moon. So at its greatest distance from Earth, it will be 432,826 km from the center of the Earth or 426,448 km in absolute altitude.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nApollo 13\u0027s record was 400,171 km in absolute altitude, set not because the distance from the moon was particularly great (although it was about 100 km greater than in past missions) but because the moon was near apogee during that flyby.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSo it would appear that Orion WILL break Apollo 13\u0027s record, not because of the Earth-Moon distance, but because of its greater distance from the moon.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"sevenperforce","CreatedById":157695,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-23T17:28:11Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224201497\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022186560\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221669151880\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022206402\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022SunlitZelkova\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n20 hours ago, SunlitZelkova said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsEmbeddedOther\u0022\u003E\n\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 data-controller=\u0022core.front.core.autosizeiframe\u0022 data-embedid=\u0022embed4241847425\u0022 scrolling=\u0022no\u0022 src=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?app=core\u0026amp;module=system\u0026amp;controller=embed\u0026amp;url=https://twitter.com/nasa_marshall/status/1595096021079564288?s=46%26t=4bl9AZjH8vN1rSa5kj1IVw\u0022 style=\u0022height:710px;\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThis tweet evidently is only giving the distance of Apollo 13\u0027s record, not stating the distance which Orion will achieve.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"kerbiloid","CreatedById":129408,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-23T18:07:52Z","Content":"\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler\u0022 data-ipsspoiler=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler_header\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cspan\u003ESpoiler\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u0022Orbits are ellipses, they said.\u00A0\u003Cbr\u003E\nSquares and cubes, they said.\u0022\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022comoving.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 data-ratio=\u002264.29\u0022 height=\u0022360\u0022 width=\u0022560\u0022 src=\u0022https://i.postimg.cc/TPRMBykk/comoving.png\u0022\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"cubinator","CreatedById":150330,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-23T21:09:37Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224201802\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022186560\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221669226872\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022129408\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022kerbiloid\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n3 hours ago, kerbiloid said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler\u0022 data-ipsspoiler=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler_header\u0022\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022#\u0022 rel=\u0022\u0022\u003E\u00A0\u003C/a\u003E \u003Cspan\u003EReveal hidden contents\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u0022Orbits are ellipses, they said.\u00A0\u003Cbr\u003E\nSquares and cubes, they said.\u0022\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://i.postimg.cc/TPRMBykk/comoving.png\u0022 title=\u0022Enlarge image\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003E\u003Cimg alt=\u0022comoving.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage ipsImage_thumbnailed\u0022 data-ratio=\u002264.29\u0022 height=\u0022360\u0022 width=\u0022560\u0022 src=\u0022https://i.postimg.cc/TPRMBykk/comoving.png\u0022\u003E\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u0022...From a certain point of view.\u0022\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Gargamel","CreatedById":64714,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-23T21:10:04Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224201761\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022186560\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221669222068\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022157695\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022sevenperforce\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n4 hours ago, sevenperforce said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSo it would appear that Orion WILL break Apollo 13\u0027s record, not because of the Earth-Moon distance, but because of its greater distance from the moon.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nStill doesn\u2019t beat Voyager. \u00A0 \u00A0Until Artemis has a meat payload, they\u2019re the same thing. \u00A0 \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Cimg alt=\u0022:)\u0022 data-emoticon=\u0022\u0022 src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_smiley.gif\u0022 title=\u0022:)\u0022\u003E\u00A0\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cspan\u003EAnd I did not appreciate how goofy that orbit is. \u00A0 \u00A0\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"sevenperforce","CreatedById":157695,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-23T22:44:07Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224201869\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022186560\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221669237804\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u002264714\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Gargamel\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n1 hour ago, Gargamel said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nStill doesn\u2019t beat Voyager. \u00A0 \u00A0Until Artemis has a meat payload, they\u2019re the same thing. \u00A0 \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Cimg alt=\u0022:)\u0022 data-emoticon=\u0022\u0022 src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_smiley.gif\u0022 title=\u0022:)\u0022\u003E\u00A0\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cspan\u003EAnd I did not appreciate how goofy that orbit is. \u00A0 \u00A0\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThen you\u0027ll hate how it looks from Earth\u0027s inertial reference frame.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022Animation_of_Artemis_I_around_Earth.gif\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 data-ratio=\u002275.00\u0022 height=\u0022420\u0022 width=\u0022560\u0022 src=\u0022https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/97/Animation_of_Artemis_I_around_Earth.gif\u0022\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nFunny that it makes a retrograde re-entry to Earth. I wonder why.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Gargamel","CreatedById":64714,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-23T23:54:17Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIt just falls from the sky. \u00A0 \u00A0Huh, guess Star Trek was right. \u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"JoeSchmuckatelli","CreatedById":154477,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-24T00:53:12Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224201908\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022186560\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221669243447\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022157695\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022sevenperforce\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n2 hours ago, sevenperforce said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThen you\u0027ll hate how it looks from Earth\u0027s inertial reference frame.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/97/Animation_of_Artemis_I_around_Earth.gif\u0022 title=\u0022Enlarge image\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003E\u003Cimg alt=\u0022Animation_of_Artemis_I_around_Earth.gif\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage ipsImage_thumbnailed\u0022 data-ratio=\u002275.00\u0022 height=\u0022420\u0022 width=\u0022560\u0022 src=\u0022https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/97/Animation_of_Artemis_I_around_Earth.gif\u0022\u003E\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nFunny that it makes a retrograde re-entry to Earth. I wonder why.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThose kinds of plots are crazy.\u00A0 Like you wouldn\u0027t guess that the paths look like that.\u00A0 First time I saw something like it was a representation of asteroid belt and the Trojans and Greeks. Kind of eye opening.\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIf you find an answer to why the retrograde, let us know!\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"intelliCom","CreatedById":209738,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-24T01:27:49Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224201908\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022186560\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221669243447\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022157695\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022sevenperforce\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n2 hours ago, sevenperforce said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThen you\u0027ll hate how it looks from Earth\u0027s inertial reference frame.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/97/Animation_of_Artemis_I_around_Earth.gif\u0022 title=\u0022Enlarge image\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003E\u003Cimg alt=\u0022Animation_of_Artemis_I_around_Earth.gif\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage ipsImage_thumbnailed\u0022 data-ratio=\u002275.00\u0022 height=\u0022420\u0022 width=\u0022560\u0022 src=\u0022https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/97/Animation_of_Artemis_I_around_Earth.gif\u0022\u003E\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nFunny that it makes a retrograde re-entry to Earth. I wonder why.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIs this relative to surface rotation, or is the 24-hour loop not considered?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAlso, gotta say, that \u003Cs\u003Eeccentric orbit\u003C/s\u003E \u003Cu\u003Edrop from the sky\u003C/u\u003E looks a little extreme for reentry of a human-rated vehicle, but maybe it does relatively softer aerobraking passes like Apollo did?.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"tater","CreatedById":119411,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-11-24T03:29:49Z","Content":"\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsEmbeddedOther\u0022\u003E\n\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 data-controller=\u0022core.front.core.autosizeiframe\u0022 data-embedid=\u0022embed5938555981\u0022 scrolling=\u0022no\u0022 src=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?app=core\u0026amp;module=system\u0026amp;controller=embed\u0026amp;url=https://twitter.com/TJ_Cooney/status/1595485220828069917\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"}]}